**Files Modified:** [JoinMeetingCard.tsx](file:///d:/meet-io/client/src/components/dashboard/JoinMeetingCard.tsx)

## The Problem
Users had to manually extract the 11-character meeting code (e.g., `ABC-DEF-GHI`) from the full invite link (`http://.../meeting/ABC-DEF-GHI`) before pasting it into the join box. The input field also had a hard `maxLength={11}` limit, preventing the paste of full URLs.

## The Solution
We enhanced the input field to be "smart" about what it accepts.

### 1. Logic Implementation
We modified the `onChange` handler to intercept the user's input/paste event and run a Regular Expression (Regex) check.

**Code Snippet:**
```typescript
onChange={(e) => {
    const val = e.target.value;
    
    // Regex Logic:
    // \/meeting\/  -> looks for "/meeting/"
    // (...)        -> capture group for the code
    // [a-zA-Z0-9]{3} -> 3 alphanumeric characters
    // -            -> hyphen separator
    const urlMatch = val.match(/\/meeting\/([a-zA-Z0-9]{3}-[a-zA-Z0-9]{3}-[a-zA-Z0-9]{3})/i);
    
    if (urlMatch && urlMatch[1]) {
        // If a URL is detected, ignore the "http..." part and just take the code
        setJoinCode(urlMatch[1].toUpperCase());
        toast.success('Meeting code extracted!');
    } else {
        // If it's just a normal code or typing, accept it as is
        setJoinCode(val.toUpperCase());
    }
}}
```

### 2. UI Changes
- **Removed `maxLength={11}`**: This was critical. By removing the limit, we allow the socket to receive the *entire* long URL string first, giving our code a chance to process it, instead of the browser cutting it off immediately.
- **Auto-Formatting**: We force `toUpperCase()` so even if a URL is lowercase, the meeting code is standardized.

## User Experience
1. User copies full link: `http://localhost:5174/meeting/ABC-DEF-GHI`
2. User pastes into input.
3. Input value instantly transforms to: `ABC-DEF-GHI`
4. User clicks "Join".
